# =============================================================================
# Worker env bundle — shared non-prod app secrets loaded into every worker.
# Copy to `non-prod.env` (gitignored) and fill in NON-PROD/dev values.
# spawn-worker.sh reads it directly; nothing to upload anywhere.
#
# RULES
#  - NON-PROD/dev values only. Never put prod DB creds or prod keys here.
#  - DO NOT set PG_* / DATABASE_URL / TEST_DB_* here — the compose forces those
#    to the local sidecars and will override anything you put in this bundle.
#  - dotenv format: KEY=VALUE, one per line, no quotes needed, `#` comments ok.
#
# TWO WAYS TO FILL THIS IN
#  (A) Prototype / tests only (`npm run check`): the test harness overrides these
#      to "test" at runtime, so literal `test` placeholders are enough — the
#      asserts in config.ts just need the vars present. No real external access.
#  (B) Dev-server use (`npm run dev`, real feature verification): use real
#      DEV-TIER keys, and add the Firebase block at the bottom. The app's
#      allowedEmailsInDev / allowedPhonesInDev whitelists keep dev from
#      notifying real users.
# =============================================================================

# --- Required (config.ts asserts these exist or it throws on boot) -----------
FIREBASE_WEB_API_KEY=test
STORAGE_BUCKET_NAME=test
TWILIO_API_TOKEN=test
SENDGRID_API_KEY=test
GOOGLE_MAPS_KEY=test
POSTHOG_EVENTS_API_KEY=test
POSTHOG_PERSONAL_API_KEY=test
POSTHOG_PROJECT_ID=test
LOCAL=true

LINEAR_USER_HANDLE=your_linear_user_handle

# --- Optional (no assert; omit for tests, set for real dev integrations) ------
# POSTHOG_HOST=https://us.i.posthog.com
# SLACK_LEAD_FORM_WEBHOOK_URL=
# SLACK_STUCK_LEAD_WEBHOOK_URL=

# --- Muaddib token tracking (required to persist run data to the API) ---------
# Generate a shared secret: openssl rand -hex 32
# Set MUADDIB_API_TOKEN to the same value in the API server env (dev + prod).
# MUADDIB_API_TOKEN=your_shared_secret_here
# MUADDIB_API_URL=https://api.dev.quotethat.com

# --- Linear MCP (required for /muadib to read tickets & post back) ------------
# Personal API key: Linear → Settings → Security & access → Personal API keys.
# The entrypoint wires the official Linear MCP (https://mcp.linear.app/mcp) with
# this as a Bearer header — no OAuth/browser flow. muadib needs read + write
# (it comments and may create sub-issues). CAUTION: this key acts in Linear AS
# YOU; use the narrowest key Linear allows, and note any all-commands worker (or
# prompt-injected ticket text) can use it.
# LINEAR_API_KEY=lin_api_...

# Your Linear display name — used by grill-me-async to @mention you in the
# clarification comment it posts when a fleet worker needs answers before
# planning. Linear's notification system (email + in-app) fires on @mentions,
# so this is the push signal that a worker is WAITING_FOR_INPUT.
# Find your display name: Linear → Settings → Account → Profile → Display name.
# If unset, the comment is still posted but without the @mention (no crash).
# LINEAR_USER_HANDLE=your-display-name

# --- Firebase dev service account (only for option B / `npm run dev`) ---------
# The app loads this as a FILE, not an env var. Provide the dev JSON base64'd;
# the worker entrypoint writes it to projects/api/src/config/keys/<filename>.
# Generate with:  base64 -i dev-firebase-sa.json | tr -d '\n'   (macOS)
#            or:  base64 -w0 dev-firebase-sa.json               (Linux)
# FIREBASE_DEV_SA_JSON_B64=
# FIREBASE_DEV_SA_FILENAME=dev.quotethat-test-firebase-adminsdk-fbsvc-54518044be.json

# --- Dispatch daemon (muaddib:start / muaddib:stop) --------------------------
# The daemon runs inside Docker (docker-compose.dispatch.yml) and auto-restarts
# when Docker Desktop starts. Before running `npm run muaddib:start`, export:
#   export CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=...   (claude setup-token)
#   export GITHUB_TOKEN=...             (repo-scoped PAT)
# Docker persists these values in the container config so restarts work without
# re-exporting. To rotate, run `npm run muaddib:stop && npm run muaddib:start`.
#
# DISPATCH_PORT sets the local HTTP port the daemon listens on (cloudflared
# tunnels it to a public HTTPS URL that Linear posts webhooks to).
# DISPATCH_WEBHOOK_SECRET signs/verifies the Linear webhook; generate with:
#   node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
# LINEAR_TEAM_ID is the Linear team UUID (not the key); find it in Linear →
# Settings → My Team → copy the ID from the URL or the API.
# MAX_DISPATCH_WORKERS caps concurrent worker containers; overflow is queued.
# DISPATCH_PORT=3999
# DISPATCH_WEBHOOK_SECRET=changeme
# LINEAR_TEAM_ID=your_team_id
# MAX_DISPATCH_WORKERS=8
#
# DISPATCH_ASSIGNEE_ID scopes this dispatcher to tickets assigned to a specific
# Linear user. When set, events for tickets assigned to any other user (or
# unassigned) are silently skipped. Required when running dispatchers on more
# than one machine — each machine should set this to its own Linear user UUID
# so only one dispatcher fires per ticket.
# Find your Linear user UUID: Linear → Settings → Account → copy the UUID from
# the URL, or run:
#   curl -s -H "Authorization: $LINEAR_API_KEY" \
#     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
#     --data '{"query":"{ viewer { id name } }"}' \
#     https://api.linear.app/graphql | jq .data.viewer
# Leave unset to dispatch any ticket regardless of assignee (single-machine setup).
# DISPATCH_ASSIGNEE_ID=your_linear_user_uuid